Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a
large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g} and @korma curry paste{50%g} and cook until
fragrant, ~{1-2%mins}.

Add the @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{600%ml} and stir to combine.

Stir the @red split lentils{50%g} through the soup, bring back to the boil, then lower to a
simmer.

Cook until the lentils are tender, ~{15-20%mins}.

Meanwhile, cut the @broccoli{1} into florets (like small trees), halving any large ones.

Pop the broccoli florets onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, sprinkle over the
@North Indian style spice mix{1/2%tsp} and @dukkah mix{1%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until the edges are crispy and slightly charred,
~{12-15%mins}.

When the soup has 5 mins remaining, put the @plain naans{2} onto a baking tray.

Sprinkle with a little @water{} and pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%mins}.

When the lentils are cooked, stir the @mango chutney{40%g} and @creme fraiche{75%g} through
the soup.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

Share the soup between your #bowls{} and top with the roasted broccoli.

Serve your naans alongside.

Enjoy!